ntrol}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Greatest Showman, The}}\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:2010s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s musical drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American biographical films]]\n[[Category:American musical drama films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about entertainers]]\n[[Category:Films about playwrights]]\n[[Category:Circus films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Debney]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Joseph Trapanese]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Peter Chernin]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Laurence Mark]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Bill Condon]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of P. T. Barnum]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Jenny Lind]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Queen Victoria on film]]\n[[Category:Musical films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:2017 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2017 American biographical musical film by Michael Gracey}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Greatest Showman\n| image          = The Greatest Showman poster.png\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Michael Gracey]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Laurence Mark]]\n* [[Peter Chernin]]\n* [[Jenno Topping]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jenny Bicks]]\n* [[Bill Condon]]\n}}\n| story          = Jenny Bicks\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|<!--Per poster billing-->\n* [[Hugh Jackman]]\n* [[Zac Efron]]\n* [[Michelle Williams (actress)|Michelle Williams]]\n* [[Rebecca Ferguson]]\n* [[Zendaya]]\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|<!--SCORE-->\n* [[John Debney]]\n* [[Joseph Trapanese]] (score)\n* [[Pasek and Paul]] (songs)\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Seamus McGarvey]]\n| editing        = {{plainlist|\n* [[Tom Cross (film editor)|Tom Cross]]\n* Robert Duffy\n* [[Joe Hutshing]]\n* [[Michael McCusker]]\n* [[Jon Poll]]\n* [[Spencer Susser]]\n}}\n| studio         = {{ubl|Laurence Mark Productions|[[Chernin Entertainment]]|[[TSG Entertainment]]}}\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|12|8|[[RMS Queen Mary 2|RMS ''Queen Mary 2'']]|2017|12|20|United States}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 104:52--><ref>{{cite web |title=''The Greatest Showman''|url=https://www.amctheatres.com/movies/the-greatest-showman-47115 |publisher=[[AMC Theatres]]|access-date=November 22, 2017}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $84{{nbsp}}million<ref name=budget>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/features/hugh-jackman-the-greatest-showman-logan-1202629864/ |title=Hugh Jackman on ''The Greatest Showman'', Saying Goodbye to Wolverine and Turning Down Bond |first=Brent |last=Lang |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 5, 2017 |accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n| gross          = $435{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=greatestshowman.htm |title=''The Greatest Showman'' (2017)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Greatest Showman''''' is a 2017 American [[musical film|musical]] [[biographical film|biographical drama film]] directed by [[Michael Gracey]] in his directorial debut, written by [[Jenny Bicks]] and [[Bill Condon]] and starring [[Hugh Jackman]], [[Zac Efron]], [[Michelle Williams (actress)|Michelle Williams]], [[Rebecca Ferguson]], and [[Zendaya]]. Featuring nine original songs from [[Benj Pasek]] and [[Justin Paul]], the film is inspired by the story of [[P.&nbsp;T. Barnum]]'s creation of [[Barnum's American Museum]] and the lives of its star attractions.\n\n[[Principal photography]] began in [[New York City]] in November 2016. The film premiered on December 8, 2017, aboard [[RMS Queen Mary 2|RMS ''Queen Mary 2'']]. It was released in the United States on December 20, 2017, by [[20th Century Fox]], seven months after [[Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus]] ceased operations, and grossed over $434{{nbsp}}million worldwide, making it the fifth-highest-grossing live-action musical of all time.\n\n''The Greatest Showman'' received mixed reviews from critics, with praise for the performances, music, and production values, but criticism for its [[artistic license]], with some reviewers calling it \"faux-inspiring and shallow\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/jumanji-welcome-to-the-jungle-is-certified-fresh/ |title=Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle is Certified Fresh |date=December 21, 2017 |accessdate=December 21, 2017 |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|last=Giles|first=Jeff}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Greatest Showman review round-up: A \"crowd-pleaser\" with a \"sinister\" side |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a845887/the-greatest-showman-review-round-up-pt-barnum-hugh-jackman/ |work=[[Digital Spy]]|first=Louise |last=McCreesh |date=December 20, 2017 |accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/1750710/this-rotten-week-predicting-all-the-money-in-the-world-reviews?story_page=2 |title=This Rotten Week: Predicting All The Money In The World Reviews |date=December 25, 2017 |accessdate=January 7, 2018|last=Nourrie|first=Doug |work=CinemaBlend}}</ref> At the [[75th Golden Globe Awards]], the film received nominations for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture&nbsp;\u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor&nbsp;\u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] for Jackman. For the song \"[[This Is Me (The Greatest Showman song)|This Is Me]]\", the film won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]] and was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] at the [[90th Academy Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2018-nominees-full-list-1202634435/ |title=Golden Globe Nominations: Complete List |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 11, 2017 |accessdate=December 11, 2017 |first=Rebecca |last=Rubin}}</ref> and won the [[Grammy Award for Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media|Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media]] at the [[61st Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>[https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/61st-annual-grammy-awards Grammy.com, 7 December 2018]</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot summaries for feature films are to be between 400 to 700 words. -->\nIn the mid-19th century, [[P.&nbsp;T. Barnum]] and his troupe perform a show at the circus (\"The Greatest Show (Part 1)\").\n\nAs a child, Barnum and his tailor father Philo work for the Hallett family. He loves their daughter Charity who is being sent to [[finishing school]]. The two keep in touch through letters (\"A Million Dreams\"), eventually marrying and raising two daughters, Caroline and Helen, in New York City. They live a humble life; though Charity is happy, Barnum craves more.\n\nBarnum loses his job as a clerk at a shipping company after the company goes bankrupt, and returns home for Caroline's birthday (\"A Million Dreams (Reprise)\"). He takes out a loan from a bank, deceiving them into accepting his former employer's lost ships as collateral. He uses this loan to set up [[Barnum's American Museum]] in downtown Manhattan, an attraction showcasing various wax models. Initially, sales are slow. On the suggestion of his children to showcase something \"alive\", Barnum searches for \"freaks\" to serve as performers for his museum (\"Come Alive\"). He gathers a large group of them, including [[bearded lady]] Lettie Lutz. This attracts a large audience despite protests and poor reviews from well-known critic [[James Gordon Bennett Sr.|James Gordon Bennett]], prompting Barnum to rename his venture \"Barnum's Circus\".\n\nSearching for ways to further his reputation, Barnum meets playwright Phillip Carlyle and convinces him to join his venture (\"The Other Side\"). Phillip is mesmerized by the African American trapeze artist Anne Wheeler, but he hides his feelings. During a trip, Phillip arranges for Barnum and his troupe to meet [[Queen Victoria]]. Afterwards, Barnum convinces famed Swedish singer [[Jenny Lind]] to perform in America with him as her manager. Lind's first American performance is a rousing success (\"Never Enough\"); during the song, Phillip and Anne are spotted by Phillip's parents as they are holding hands. As Barnum gains favor with the aristocratic patrons, he begins to distance himself from his troupe as he advises them to work on their performances without him. Dejected, they decide to stand against their local harassers (\"This Is Me\").\n\nPhillip and Anne attend the theatre but they run into Phillip's parents, who chastise Phillip for \"parading around with the help\". Anne runs off, and Phillip angrily berates them, then chases Anne and tries to convince her that they can be together, but she rejects him (\"[[Rewrite the Stars]]\"). As Barnum takes Lind on a US tour, Charity feels isolated from her husband as she stays home with their daughters (\"Tightrope\"). While on tour, Lind begins falling in love with Barnum. When he refuses her advances, she threatens to quit and orchestrates a kiss with him at the end of her last show, which is photographed by the press (\"Never Enough (Reprise)\").\n\nBarnum returns home to find his circus on fire, caused by a fight between the protesters and the troupe. Phillip runs into the burning building, believing that Anne is still inside, and suffers serious injuries before being rescued by Barnum. Barnum gets word from a sympathetic Bennett that the culprits have been caught and that Lind has canceled her tour after her and Barnum's \"scandal\". Barnum's mansion is foreclosed upon and Charity takes their daughters to her parents' home.\n\nDevastated by his selfishness, Barnum retreats to a local bar where his troupe find him and explain that despite their disappointments, they still consider themselves a family that needs him. Inspired, he resolves to start a new show and not let ambition overtake his love (\"From Now On\"). Phillip wakes in a hospital with Anne by his side. Barnum finds Charity and they mend their relationship.\n\nBarnum is faced with the financial difficulty of rebuilding the circus, but the recovering Phillip steps in, offering to use his share of the circus's profits to rebuild it under condition of becoming a full partner, which Barnum happily accepts. To save money, Barnum transforms the enterprise into an open-air tent circus by the docks.\n\nThe revamped circus is a huge success (\"The Greatest Show (Part 2)\"). Barnum gives full control of the show to Phillip to spend more time with his family.\n\n==Cast==\n{{cast list|\n* [[Hugh Jackman]] as [[P.&nbsp;T. Barnum]], an ambitious showman and entrepreneur\n** [[Ellis Rubin (actor)|Ellis Rubin]] as Young P.{{nbsp}}T. Barnum\n*** Ziv Zaifman provides Young P.{{nbsp}}T. Barnum's singing voice\n* [[Zac Efron]] as Phillip Carlyle, a [[playwright]] who becomes Barnum's partner\n* [[Michelle Williams (actress)|Michelle Williams]] as Charity Hallett-Barnum, the wife of P.{{nbsp}}T. Barnum\n** Skylar Dunn as Young Charity\n* [[Rebecca Ferguson]] as [[Jenny Lind]], a famous Swedish singer known as the \"Swedish Nightingale\"\n** [[Loren Allred]] provides Lind's singing voice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900007822/discover-utahs-loren-allred-the-voice-behind-the-hit-song-never-enough-from-the-greatest-showman-soundtrack.html|work=[[Deseret News]]|title=Discover Utah's Loren Allred, the voice behind the hit song 'Never Enough' from ''The Greatest Showman'' soundtrack|last=Hayes|first=Heather|date=January 17, 2018|accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BbcfDdtFikjQTMkqssrczhyJZ4NzVvLKR5Tr4w0/|website=[[Instagram]]|title=[post]|last=Allred|first=Loren|date=November 13, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Zendaya]] as Anne Wheeler, an acrobat and trapeze artist\n* [[Keala Settle]] as Lettie Lutz, a [[bearded lady]]. She is a composite character partly based on [[Josephine Clofullia]] and [[Annie Jones (bearded woman)|Annie Jones]].\n* [[Yahya Abdul-Mateen II]] as W.{{nbsp}}D. Wheeler, an acrobat and Anne's older brother\n* [[Natasha Liu Bordizzo]] as Deng Yan, a Chinese acrobat and blade specialist\n* [[Paul Sparks]] as [[James Gordon Bennett Sr.|James Gordon Bennett]], the founder, editor and publisher of the ''[[New York Herald]]''\n* [[Sam Humphrey]] as Charles Stratton, a dwarf performer who is also known by his stage name [[General Tom Thumb]]. In performing this role, Humphrey had to walk on his knees since he was taller than the actual Stratton.\n** James Babson provides Stratton's singing and speaking voice.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n* Austyn Johnson as Caroline Barnum, Barnum's older daughter\n* Cameron Seely as Helen Barnum, Barnum's younger daughter\n* [[Eric Anderson (actor)|Eric Anderson]] as Mr. O'Malley, a former pickpocket whom Barnum employs at his circus after failing to rob him. O'Malley handles different tasks like staffing the front of the house, selling tickets, reading the reviews, fending off the protesters, producing the posters and promotional materials, and posting circus playbills everywhere.\n* Daniel Everidge as The Lord of Leeds, a 500-pound man who is based on Teodulo Valenzuela\n* Radu Spinghel as Vasily \"O'Clancy\" Palvos, an \"Irish Giant\"\n* Timothy Hughes as the [[Strongman (strength athlete)|Strongman]], a man with enhanced strength who is based on [[Angus MacAskill]]<ref name=\"No More Living in the Shadows\"/>\n* Luciano Acuna Jr. as Walter, the Dog Boy who is based on [[Fedor Jeftichew]]\n* Danial Son and Yusaku Komori as [[Chang and Eng Bunker]], the \"[[Conjoined twins|Siamese Twins]]\"\n* Nick Jantz as Jeff Harris, the Juggler\n* Kenneth Chan as the [[Human cannonball|Human Cannonball]]\n* Martha Nichols as Woman in Gold, an African-American woman in gold clothing with gold spots on her\n* Jonathan Redavid as [[Frank Lentini]], the Three-Legged Man. He was credited as \"Dancer Oddity #1\".<ref name=\"No More Living in the Shadows\">[https://no-more-living-in-the-shadows.tumblr.com/tagged/circus] at Tumbler</ref>\n* Shannon Holtzapffel as Prince Constantine, the Tattooed Man who is based on [[Captain George Costentenus]]. He was credited as \"Dancer Oddity #2\".<ref name=\"No More Living in the Shadows\"/>\n* Jeremy Hudson as The Elephant-Skinned Man, a man who is based on [[Ralph Krooner]]. He was credited as \"Dancer Oddity #3\".<ref name=\"No More Living in the Shadows\"/>\n* Taylor James as [[Human Blockhead|Blockhead]], a man with facial piercing that is based on [[Melvin Burkhart]]. He is credited as \"Dancing Oddity #4\".<ref name=\"No More Living in the Shadows\"/>\n* Chelsea Caso as [[Tattooed lady|Tattooed Lady]], a woman covered in tattoos who is based on Nora Hildebrant. She is credited as \"Dancing Oddity #5\".<ref name=\"No More Living in the Shadows\"/>\n* Caoife Coleman and Mishay Petronelli as the [[Albino]] Twins, two albino women in white clothes who are based on Mary and Florence Martin. They were credited as \"Dancer Oddity #6\" and \"Dancer Oddity #7\".<ref name=\"No More Living in the Shadows\"/>\n* Khasan Brasilford as Albino Man, a white-haired man in white clothes. He was credited as \"Ensemble Dancer #1\".<ref name=\"No More Living in the Shadows\"/>\n* Alex Wong as Oriental Man, a Chinese man dressed in an oriental outfit. He was credited as \"Ensemble Dancer #2\".<ref name=\"No More Living in the Shadows\"/>\n* Julius Rubio as Golden Boy, a man in gold clothing with gold spots on him. He was credited as \"Ensemble Dancer #3\".<ref name=\"No More Living in the Shadows\"/>\n* Vincent-Oliver Noiseux as Devil Boy, a performer with horns. He was credited as \"Ensemble Dancer #4\".<ref name=\"No More Living in the Shadows\"/>\n* DeAnna Walters and Jessica Castro as the Voodoo Twins, two African-American twins. They are credited as \"Ensemble Dancer #5\" and \"Ensemble Dancer #6\".<ref name=\"No More Living in the Shadows\"/>\n* Najla Gilam as Snake Dancer, a [[snake charmer]] who is based on [[Nala Damajanti]]. She was credited as \"Ensemble Dancer #7\".<ref name=\"No More Living in the Shadows\"/>\n* Christina Glur as the Egyptian Lady, a woman in a fiery red costume with matching hair and an all-seeing eye tattooed on the palm of her right hand. She was credited as \"Ensemble Dancer #8\".<ref name=\"No More Living in the Shadows\"/>\n* Byron Jennings as Mr. Carlyle, Phillip's father\n* [[Betsy Aidem]] as Mrs. Carlyle, Phillip's mother\n* [[Damian Young]] as Mr. Winthrop\n* [[Tina Benko]] as Mrs. Winthrop\n* [[Will Swenson (actor)|Will Swenson]] as Philo Barnum, a tailor and the late father of P.{{nbsp}}T. Barnum\n* Linda Marie Larson as Gertrude Stratton, Charles Stratton's mother\n* [[Fredric Lehne]] as Benjamin Hallett, Charity's father and Barnum's disapproving father-in-law\n* Kathryn Meisle as Hannah Hallett, Charity's mother and Barnum's mother-in-law\n* [[Gayle Rankin]] as [[Queen Victoria]], the Queen of the United Kingdom\n* [[Shuler Hensley]] as Lead Protester, the leader of the anti-freak protesters\n* Adam Haas Hunter as protester\n* James Andrew O'Connor as firefighter\n}}\n\nSandou Trio Russian Bar makes an uncredited background cameo during the revamped circus scene.<ref>https://talentrecap.com/sandou-trio-russian-bar-6-facts-about-this-unique-agt-champions-act/</ref>\n\nPointe Ballerinas portrayed by Emerson Tate Alexander, Victoria Llodra, Louise Hindsbo, Laci Justice, GiaNina Paolantonio, Rachel Quiner, Madison Smith, and Brando Speach\n\n==Production==\nDuring rehearsals for the [[81st Academy Awards]] in 2009, producers [[Laurence Mark]] and [[Bill Condon]] compared host Jackman to Barnum. After Jackman expressed interest in a Barnum project, Mark and Condon approached [[Jenny Bicks]], a writer for the ceremony. She and Condon wrote ''The Greatest Showman''.<ref name=\"mchenry20190222\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/02/the-history-of-hugh-jackmans-oscars-opening-number.html |title=The Behind-the-Scenes History of Hugh Jackman\u2019s Opening Number at the 2009 Oscars |last=McHenry |first=Jackson |date=2019-02-22 |website=www.vulture.com |access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref> The project was first announced in 2009, with Jackman already set for the title role.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jagernauth |first1=Kevin |title=Michael Gracey To Direct Hugh Jackman Musical ''The Greatest Showman On Earth''|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2011/08/michael-gracey-to-direct-hugh-jackman-musical-the-greatest-showman-on-earth-116851/ |date=August 11, 2011 |website=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=July 10, 2017}}</ref> In August 2011, [[Michael Gracey]] was chosen to direct.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McClintock |first1=Pamela |last2=Kit |first2=Borys |title=Michael Gracey to Direct ''The Greatest Showman on Earth''|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/michael-gracey-direct-greatest-showman-224459 |accessdate=July 12, 2016 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=August 17, 2011}}</ref> In 2013, Fox hired lyricists [[Pasek and Paul]] to write the songs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/the-greatest-showman-benj-pasek-justin-paul-oscars-interview-1202195785/ |title=''The Greatest Showman'' Songwriters Benj Pasek & Justin Paul On The Revitalization Of The Original Hollywood Musical |date=November 17, 2017 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Grobar|first=Matt|accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 15, 2016, [[Zac Efron]] began negotiations to star in the film,<ref name=\"EfronTalks\">{{cite news |last1=McNary |first1=Dave |title=Zac Efron in Talks to Join Hugh Jackman's ''Greatest Showman'' (Exclusive) |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/zac-efron-hugh-jackman-greatest-showman-1201796420/ |accessdate=June 16, 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 15, 2016}}</ref> and in July 2016, [[Michelle Williams (actress)|Michelle Williams]] was cast.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McNary |first=Dave |title=Michelle Williams in Talks for Hugh Jackman's ''Greatest Showman on Earth''|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/michelle-williams-hugh-jackman-greatest-showman-on-earth-1201809404/ |date=July 6, 2016 |access-date=January 5, 2018 |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pulver |first=Andrew |title=Michelle Williams and Zac Efron sought for PT Barnum biopic |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jul/08/michelle-williams-zac-efron-greatest-showman-on-earth-pt-barnum |date=July 8, 2016 |access-date=January 5, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Jaafar |first=Ali |title=Michelle Williams In Talks To Join ''The Greatest Showman'' With Hugh Jackman |url=https://deadline.com/2016/07/michelle-williams-in-talks-to-join-hugh-jackman-p-t-barnum-in-the-greatest-showman-on-earth-1201783215/ |date=July 6, 2016 |access-date=January 5, 2018 |journal=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Giroux |first=Jack |title=Michelle Williams Joins Hugh Jackman in ''The Greatest Showman on Earth''|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/michelle-williams-in-the-greatest-showman-on-earth/ |date=July 7, 2016 |access-date=January 5, 2018 |journal=[[SlashFilm]]}}</ref> The film was choreographed by [[Ashley Wallen]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Meet the Man Behind Hugh Jackman's Moves in ''The Greatest Showman''|url=http://www.dancemagazine.com/the-greatest-showman-ashley-wallen-2518470024.html |accessdate=December 19, 2017 |work=[[Dance Magazine]] |last=Gold |first=Sylvaine|date=December 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nRehearsals on the film began in October 2016 in [[New York City]], and [[principal photography]] began on November 22, 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=''The Greatest Showman'', starring Hugh Jackman & Zac Efron, begins filming in NYC soon! |url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2016/11/10/greatest-showman-starring-hugh-jackman-zac-efron-begins-filming-nyc-soon/ |accessdate=November 17, 2016 |work=On Location Vacations |date=November 10, 2016 |author=Christine}}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\nIn December 2017, it was reported that [[James Mangold]], who had worked with Jackman on several projects (including 2017's ''[[Logan (film)|Logan]]''), had been brought in to serve as an executive producer during the film's post-production. In an interview, director Michael Gracey noted, \"There were eight producers on this film, and it was amazing having one of them be a filmmaker.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Stack |first=Tim |url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/12/22/the-greatest-showman-michael-gracey-musical-numbers-broadway/ |title=''The Greatest Showman'' Director On The Epic Musical Numbers And If It Could Head To Broadway |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=December 22, 2017 |accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n===Musical numbers===\n[[File:Zac Efron and Zendaya Coleman in 2017.jpg|thumb|Zac Efron and Zendaya being interviewed regarding \"Rewrite the Stars\" and ''The Greatest Showman'']]\n[[Pasek and Paul|Benj Pasek and Justin Paul]] wrote all the songs appearing in the film.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Burlingame |first=Jon |title='This Is Me' From ''The Greatest Showman'' Is an Anthem for Outcasts |url=https://variety.com/2018/music/awards/greatest-showman-song-this-is-me-1202654029/ |date=January 4, 2018 |access-date=January 17, 2018 |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n# \"[[The Greatest Show]]\" \u2013 Hugh Jackman, The Greatest Showman Ensemble\n# \"[[A Million Dreams]]\" \u2013 Ziv Zaifman, Jackman, Michelle Williams\n# \"[[A Million Dreams#Reprise|A Million Dreams (Reprise)]]\" \u2013 Austyn Johnson, Cameron Seely, Jackman\n# \"Come Alive\" \u2013 Jackman, Keala Settle, Daniel Everidge, Zendaya\n# \"The Other Side\" \u2013 Jackman & Zac Efron\n# \"Never Enough\" \u2013 [[Loren Allred]]\n# \"[[This Is Me (Keala Settle song)|This Is Me]]\" \u2013 Settle & Ensemble\n# \"[[Rewrite the Stars]]\" \u2013 Efron, Zendaya \n# \"Tightrope\" \u2013 Williams\n# \"Never Enough (Reprise)\" \u2013 Allred\n# \"From Now On\" \u2013 Jackman, Ensemble\n# \"[[The Greatest Show]]\" \u2013 Jackman, Efron, Settle, Zendaya, Ensemble\n\n===Soundtrack===\n{{Main|The Greatest Showman: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack}}\nThe soundtrack album is produced by [[Justin Paul]], [[Benj Pasek]], [[Greg Wells]], [[Kevin Weaver]] and [[Pete Ganbarg]], featuring the eleven tracks performed by the cast. In the United Kingdom, on March 23, 2018, it became only the second album in 30 years to achieve 11 consecutive weeks at number 1, equalling the record set by [[Adele]]'s ''[[21 (Adele album)|21]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-greatest-showman-soundtrack-equals-adele-s-massive-uk-chart-record__22377/|title=''The Greatest Showman'' soundtrack equals Adele's massive UK chart record|date=March 23, 2018|accessdate=April 18, 2018|last=Copsey|first=Rob|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-46704440 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line -->|work=BBC News|title=The Greatest Showman soundtrack beats Adele's UK album chart record|date=December 28, 2018|access-date=February 18, 2019}}</ref> {{as of|2019|1|25|df=US}}, the album has spent the sixth most time at number one at 28 non-consecutive weeks, matching the Beatles' ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/albums-with-the-most-weeks-at-number-1-on-the-official-albums-chart__23234/|last=Copsey|first=Rob|title=Albums with the most weeks at Number 1 on the Official Albums Chart|publisher=Official Charts Company|date=January 25, 2019|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===''The Greatest Showman: Reimagined''===\n{{Main|The Greatest Showman: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack#The Greatest Showman: Reimagined}}\nOn November 16, 2018, a remix album was also released, ''The Greatest Showman: Reimagined'', which features covers of songs from the soundtrack by musicians including [[James Arthur]] and [[Anne-Marie (singer)|Anne-Marie]], [[Sara Bareilles]], [[Kelly Clarkson]], [[Kesha]], [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], [[Panic! At the Disco]], [[Years & Years]] and [[Jess Glynne]], and [[Zac Brown Band]] among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/the-greatest-showman-reimagined-soundtrack/|title=\u2018The Greatest Showman\u2019 Soundtrack Is Getting Reimagined with Kelly Clarkson, Panic! at the Disco & More|website=Slashfilm|last=Anderton|first=Ethan|date=October 9, 2018|accessdate=October 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/the-greatest-showman-covers-album/|title=\u2018The Greatest Showman\u2019 Is Getting a Covers Album Featuring P!nk, Kelly Clarkson, and More|website=Collider|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|date=October 9, 2018|accessdate=October 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n[[File:The Greatest Showman Japan Premiere Red Carpet- Hugh Jackman (38435514650).jpg|thumb|[[Hugh Jackman]] at the film's Japanese premiere on February 13, 2018]]\n''The Greatest Showman'' held its premiere on December 8, 2017, aboard [[RMS Queen Mary 2|RMS ''Queen Mary 2'']], while it was docked in [[New York City]]. The film was then released in the United States on December 20, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/cunard-to-broadcast-live-red-carpet-from-the-greatest-showman-world-premiere-on-flagship-queen-mary-2-300567705.html |title=Cunard to Broadcast Live Red Carpet from ''The Greatest Showman'' World Premiere on Flagship Queen Mary 2 |work=[[PR Newswire]]|date=December 6, 2017 |accessdate=2017-12-08|author=[[Cunard Line]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/the-greatest-showman-trailer-hugh-jackman-zac-efron-zendaya-video-1202206888/ |title=''The Greatest Showman'' Trailer: Hugh Jackman's Singing & Dancing Ringmaster|last=Tartaglione |first=Nancy |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 13, 2017 |accessdate=2017-11-14}}</ref>\n\nAs with [[Beauty and the Beast (2017 film)|Disney's live-action ''Beauty and the Beast'']], a sing-along version of the film was released in the United Kingdom on 23 February 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/greatest-showman-film-0 |title=''The Greatest Showman'': Sing-Along (PG) |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=2018-01-25 |accessdate=2018-02-11}}</ref> The film had a limited [[IMAX]] release on 2 February 2018.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n===Marketing===\nOn June 28, 2017, 20th Century Fox released the first international [[Trailer (promotion)|trailer]] to promote the film. On November 13, 2017, the second trailer was released.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gq.com/story/greatest-showman-trailer |title =Hugh Jackman Is Fun Again in ''The Greatest Showman'' Trailer|last=Rivera |first=Joshua |date=June 28, 2017 |website=[[GQ (magazine)|GQ]] |access-date=2017-11-24}}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, 2017, [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] televised a live performance of \"Come Alive\" from [[Warner Bros. Studios]] during its live musical special ''[[A Christmas Story Live!]]'' (which was based on fellow Pasek and Paul work ''[[A Christmas Story: The Musical]]''). The number featured the film's stars and a cast of 150 dancers.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/the-greatest-showman-hugh-jackman-zac-efron-zendaya-keala-settle-live-movie-trailer-a-christmas-story-1202228961/ |title=''The Greatest Showman'' Live Movie Trailer Electrifies During ''A Christmas Story Live''|last=Ramos |first=Dino-Ray |date=December 18, 2017 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=2017-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.adweek.com/creativity/hugh-jackmans-live-ad-last-night-for-the-greatest-showman-was-quite-the-circus/ |title=Hugh Jackman's Live Ad Last Night for ''The Greatest Showman'' Was Quite the Circus |work=[[Adweek]]|last=Natividad|first=Angela|access-date=2017-12-18|date=2017-12-18}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nIn the United States, the film was released via digital download on March 20, 2018, and was released on DVD, Blu-ray, and 4K Ultra HD on April 10, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/aw/d/B077R32LVQ/ref=tmm_blu_title_0?ie=UTF8&qid=1520232130&sr=8-1 |publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon]]|title=''The Greatest Showman'': Movie Plus Sing-Along|accessdate=2018-04-18}}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, the film was released first on digital download on April 27, 2018, while DVD, Blu-ray, and 4K Ultra HD copies went on sale on May 14, 2018. These versions included the sing-along version, two hours of behind-the-scenes footage, and music machine jukebox features.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/films/925214/The-Greatest-Showman-home-release-date-DVD-Blu-ray-Digital-Download-Hugh-Jackman |title=''The Greatest Showman'' home release dates REVEALED for Blu-ray, DVD and Digital Download|last=Simpson|first=George|work=[[Daily Express]]|date=2018-02-28|accessdate=2018-04-18}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''The Greatest Showman'' spent 219 days in release, closing on July 26, 2018, having grossed $174.3{{nbsp}}million in the United States and Canada, and $260.7{{nbsp}}million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $435{{nbsp}}million, against a production budget of $84{{nbsp}}million.<ref name=BOM/> It is the third-highest-grossing musical ever in North America and also the third-highest globally, and ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' estimated the film would turn a profit of $50\u2013100 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/the-greatest-showman-crosses-400-million-global-box-office-fox-marketing-analysis-future-plans-1202353898/ |title=This Is $400M+: ''The Greatest Showman'' Hits WW Milestone On Feel-Good Legs|first=Nancy |last=Tartaglione |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 29, 2018 |accessdate=March 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''The Greatest Showman'' was released alongside ''[[Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle]]'', and was projected to gross around $21{{nbsp}}million from 3,006 theaters over its first six days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/2017-domestic-box-office-the-last-jedi-2016-all-time-record-1202215287/ |title=Does 2017's Domestic Box Office Stand A Chance To Eclipse Last Year's All-Time $11.4B Record? |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 28, 2017 |accessdate=November 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/box-office/jumanji-greatest-showman-pitch-perfect-star-wars-box-office-1202644785/ |title=''Jumanji'', ''Greatest Showman'', ''Pitch Perfect'' to Challenge the ''Star Wars'' Box Office Force |first=Dave |last=McNary |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 19, 2017 |accessdate=December 19, 2017}}</ref> It took in $2.5{{nbsp}}million on its first day and $2.1{{nbsp}}million on its second. Over the three-day weekend, it grossed $9{{nbsp}}million (for a six-day total of $19{{nbsp}}million), finishing fourth at the box office, behind ''[[Star Wars: The Last Jedi]]'', ''Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle'' and ''[[Pitch Perfect 3]]''.<ref name=opening>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/last-jedi-dwayne-johnson-jumanji-zac-efron-greatest-showman-box-office-1202230784/ |title='Last Jedi' Now At $99M, 'Jumanji' Huge At $72M+; 'All The Money In The World' Opens To $2.6M \u2013 Christmas Weekend |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 26, 2017 |accessdate=December 26, 2017}}</ref> In its second weekend, the film grossed $15.5{{nbsp}}million, again finishing 4th at the box office.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/last-jedi-jumanji-new-years-weekend-box-office-2018-1202233711/ |title='Last Jedi' & 'Jumanji' Duel For No. 1 Over New Year's Weekend As 2017 Box Office Closes With $11.1B \u2013 Sunday Update |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 31, 2017 |accessdate=December 31, 2017}}</ref> The weekend-to-weekend increase of 76.3% marked the largest ever for a film playing in over 3,000 theaters, and the fourth biggest ever.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/smallestdrops.htm?page=DROP3000&p=.htm |title=Smallest Second Weekend Drop: 1982\u2013Present |work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=January 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2017/12/31/hugh-jackmans-the-greatest-showman-just-set-a-new-box-office-record/#2425fa837f7e |title=Hugh Jackman's ''The Greatest Showman'' Just Set A New Box Office Record|first=Scott |last=Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=December 31, 2017 |accessdate=January 1, 2018}}</ref> In its third week, the film dropped 11% to $14{{nbsp}}million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/01/insidious-the-last-key-last-jedi-jumanji-weekend-box-office-1202236009/ |title='Jumanji' Goes Wild With $36M; 'Insidious' Rises To $29M+ \u2013 Sunday AM B.O. Update |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=January 7, 2018 |accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> The film made $13{{nbsp}}million in its fourth weekend and $11{{nbsp}}million in its fifth, finishing 4th and 5th at the box office, respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/01/den-of-thieves-12-strong-jumanji-welcome-to-the-jungle-weekend-box-office-1202262795/ |title=January Slows As ''Jumanji'' Takes No. 1 For 3rd Weekend With $19M To $20M; Older Guy Pics ''12 Strong'' & ''Den Of Thieves'' In Mid-Teens |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=January 21, 2018 |accessdate=January 21, 2018}}</ref> The film continued to hold well in its sixth week of release, grossing $9.5{{nbsp}}million and returning to 4th place,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/01/maze-runner-death-cure-weekend-box-office-1202269925/ |title=Fox Controls Close To 40% Of Weekend B.O. Led By ''Maze Runner'' & Oscar Holdovers; ''Hostiles'' Gallops Past $10M |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=January 28, 2018 |accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref> and again finished fourth in its seventh week, this time grossing $7.8{{nbsp}}million (a drop of just 18%).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/maze-runner-winchester-jumanji-super-bowl-weekend-box-office-1202277031/ |title=''Jumanji'' Poised To Be Dwayne Johnson's Highest Grossing Pic Of All-Time Stateside After Super Bowl Weekend Rebound |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=February 4, 2018 |accessdate=February 4, 2018}}</ref> It is the 14th-highest-grossing film that never reached first place at the American box office.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/domestic/never1.htm |title=Top Grossing Movies that never hit #1, the Top 5 or Top 10 |work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=January 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 56% based on 243 reviews, and an [[average rating]] of 5.93/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''The Greatest Showman'' tries hard to dazzle the audience with a Barnum-style sense of wonder\u2014but at the expense of its complex subject's far more intriguing real-life story.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_greatest_showman_2017 |title=''The Greatest Showman'' (2017)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 48 out of 100, based on 43 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-greatest-showman |title=''The Greatest Showman'' Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it 4.5 out of 5 stars and a 70% \"definite recommend\".<ref name=opening/>\n\n[[Owen Gleiberman]] of [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']] gave the film a positive review, writing, \"''The Greatest Showman'' is a concoction, the kind of film where all the pieces click into place, yet at an hour and 45 minutes it flies by, and the link it draws between P.{{nbsp}}T. Barnum and the spirit of today is more than hype.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/the-greatest-showman-review-hugh-jackman-1202644784/ |title=Film Review: ''The Greatest Showman''|last=Gleiberman |first=Owen |date=December 20, 2017 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=December 20, 2017}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film 3/4 stars, saying, \"With all that corn and cheese and old-timey sentiment, ''The Greatest Showman'' ends up scoring some very timely social arguments. P.{{nbsp}}T. Barnum himself would have approved the dramatic sleight of hand.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/catchy-songs-steal-the-show-in-the-greatest-showman/ |title=Catchy songs steal the show in ''The Greatest Showman''|date=December 20, 2017 |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |accessdate=December 20, 2017 |last=Roeper |first=Richard}}</ref> Steve Persall of ''[[Tampa Bay Times]]'' gave the film an 'A', and said, \"''The Greatest Showman'' is the feel-good movie the holiday season needs,\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tampabay.com/features/movies/Why-The-Greatest-Showman-is-the-feel-good-movie-the-holiday-season-needs_163564515 |title=Why ''The Greatest Showman'' is the feel-good movie the holiday season needs |date=December 20, 2017 |work=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |last=Persall |first=Steve|accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref> while William Bibbiani of [[IGN]] gave ''The Greatest Showman'' a score of 7.9/10, and called the film, \"wildly entertaining\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2017/12/20/the-greatest-showman-review |title=''The Greatest Showman'' review |date=December 20, 2017 |work=[[IGN]]|accessdate=April 18, 2018|last=Bibbiani |first=William}}</ref>\n\nBritton Peele of ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' said, \"The story is interesting and the beats are well acted, but it's the musical numbers that make ''The Greatest Showman''.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guidelive.com/movie-reviews/2017/12/19/greatest-showman-hugh-jackman-zendaya-zac-efron |title=Catchy musical ''The Greatest Showman'', like its central character, reshapes truth for entertainment |date=December 20, 2017|work=[[The Dallas Morning News]] \u2013 GuideLive|last=Peele |first=Britton|accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref> Jackie K Cooper of ''[[HuffPost]]'' gave the film a score of 10/10 and wrote, \"You will be overwhelmed by the music and magic that explode on the screen. The film has a message that should resonate with today's world concerning acceptance and courage.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/the-greatest-showman-is-movie-magic_us_5a3c6921e4b06cd2bd03d98a |title=''The Greatest Showman'' Is Movie Magic |date=December 21, 2017 |work=[[HuffPost]]|last=Cooper |first=Jackie K|accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref> Hugh Armitage of ''[[Digital Spy]]'' said, \"''The Greatest Showman'' is a broad and solid crowd-pleaser. An undemanding spectacle for all the family.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/review/a845799/greatest-showman-review/ |title=''The Greatest Showman'' review \u2013 An undemanding spectacle for all the family |date=December 20, 2017 |work=[[Digital Spy]]|last=Armitage |first=Hugh}}</ref> Alan Jones of the ''[[Radio Times]]'' called it \"A joyously uplifting potpourri of visual resplendence, stylish choreography and solid gold magic, one engineered to approximate the lavish spectacle the movie musical once offered.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/film/2017-12-20/the-greatest-showman-review-pure-musical-entertainment-of-a-sumptuous-vintage/ |title=''The Greatest Showman'' review: \"pure musical entertainment of a sumptuous vintage\" |first=Alan |last=Jones |date=December 20, 2017 |accessdate=December 20, 2017 |work=[[Radio Times]]}}</ref>\n\nSheila O'Malley of [[RogerEbert.com]] gave it 3.5/4, stating \"''The Greatest Showman'' is an unabashed piece of pure entertainment punctuated by memorable songs.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-greatest-showman-2017 |title=''The Greatest Showman''|date=December 20, 2017 |work=[[RogerEbert.com]]|accessdate=April 18, 2018 |last=O'Malley |first=Sheila}}</ref> Douglas Davidson of CLTure called the film, \"An undeniable spectacle with a infectious soundtrack, a movie that dazzles and delights.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://clture.org/the-greatest-showman/ |title=''The Greatest Showman'' is an undeniable spectacle with a infectious soundtrack |date=December 15, 2017 |work=CLTure|last=Davidson|first=Douglas|accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref> [[James Berardinelli]] of ReelViews gave the film a 3/4 score, and said, \"The film has show-stopping well-choreographed numbers with catchy tunes,\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/greatest-showman-the |title=''The Greatest Showman'' film review |date=December 21, 2017 |work=ReelViews |last=Berardinelli |first=James |accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref> and Calvin Wilson of the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' called the film \"highly enjoyable.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/movies/reviews/hugh-jackman-shines-in-the-greatest-showman/article_bc263aa2-42ad-55a8-826a-b949b70706da.html |title=Hugh Jackman shines in ''The Greatest Showman''|date=December 20, 2017 |work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |last=Wilson |first=Calvin |accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCarl Kozlowski of ''[[Pasadena Weekly]]'' gave the film an 'A', calling it \"Groundbreaking & grandly innovative.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pasadenaweekly.com/2017/12/21/the-last-jedi-downsizing-and-the-greatest-showman-provide-an-eclectic-feast-for-the-senses/ |title=''The Greatest Showman'' provide an eclectic feast for the senses |date=December 21, 2017 |work=[[Pasadena Weekly]]|last=Kozlowski|first=Carl|accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref> Sean P. Means of ''[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]'' gave ''The Greatest Showman'' 3.5/4 stars, stating, \"A strong cast give emotional power to this romanticized, tune-filled biography.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sltrib.com/artsliving/movies/2017/12/20/hugh-jackman-and-some-utah-grown-talent-deliver-barnums-bravado-in-musical-the-greatest-showman/ |title=Hugh Jackman and some Utah-grown talent deliver Barnum's bravado in musical ''The Greatest Showman''|date=December 20, 2017 |work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]] |last=Means |first=Sean P. |accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref> Manuela Lazic of ''[[Little White Lies (magazine)|Little White Lies]]'' gave it 4/5, saying, \"''The Greatest Showman'' deserves to become a Christmas classic. The film's severe romanticism and ridiculous but affecting enthusiasm make it irresistibly life-affirming.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lwlies.com/reviews/the-greatest-showman/ |title=''The Greatest Showman'' Review |date=December 20, 2017 |work=[[Little White Lies (magazine)|Little White Lies]]|last=Lazic|first=Manuela|accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref> Pete Hammond of ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' gave the film 4 out of 5 stars and called it, \"A fantasia of song and dance, a joyous exercise in pure entertainment that is made for the holiday crowd.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/greatest-showman-review-hugh-jackman-zendaya-zac-efron-p-t-barnum-1202230371/ |title=''The Greatest Showman'' Review: Hugh Jackman Sings And Dances His Way Into Holiday Hearts In Lively Family Musical |date=December 20, 2017 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Hammond|first=Pete|accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nConversely, [[Mick LaSalle]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' gave the film a negative review, criticizing the songs and characters and saying \"There's idiotic, and there's magnificent, but ''The Greatest Showman'' is that special thing that happens sometimes. It's magnificently idiotic. It's an awful mess, but it's flashy. The temptation is to cover your face and watch it through your fingers, because it's so earnest and embarrassing and misguided\u2014and yet it's well made.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.sfgate.com/movies/article/Greatest-Showman-starring-Hugh-Jackman-as-12440272.php |title=''Greatest Showman'' starring Hugh Jackman as Barnum magnificently idiotic|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|first=Mick |last=LaSalle |date=December 20, 2017 |accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref> In a negative review for ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', David Rooney wrote \"This ersatz portrait of American big-top tent impresario P.{{nbsp}}T. Barnum is all smoke and mirrors, no substance. It hammers pedestrian themes of family, friendship and inclusivity while neglecting the fundaments of character and story.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/greatest-showman-film-1067827 |title=''The Greatest Showman'': Film Review |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 20, 2017 |accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', [[Peter Travers]] gave the film 1.5 out of 4 stars, saying, \"How do you cast a virtuoso Hugh Jackman as P.{{nbsp}}T. Barnum, spare no expense in production values, add a score by Oscar and Tony winners Benj Pasek and Justin Paul and still end up with the shrill blast of nothing that is ''The Greatest Showman''? Ask first-time director Michael Gracey, who cut his teeth on commercials and music videos without ever mastering the crucial knack of building snippets of musical comedy and drama into a satisfying whole.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Travers |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Travers |title=Review: ''The Greatest Showman'' Is 'a Shrill Blast of Nothing' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/peter-travers-on-greatest-showman-shrill-blast-of-nothing-w514499 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=December 19, 2017 |accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref> Justin Chang of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote that the film's failures \"are rooted in something deeper: a dispiriting lack of faith in the audience's intelligence, and a dawning awareness of its own aesthetic hypocrisy. You've rarely seen a more straight-laced musical about the joys of letting your freak flag fly.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-greatest-showman-review-20171220-story.html |title=''The Greatest Showman'' turns Hugh Jackman's P.{{nbsp}}T. Barnum into a hero, and cons the audience in the process |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=December 20, 2017 |accessdate=December 21, 2017|last=Chang |first=Justin}}</ref>\n\nThe film has been criticized for [[Whitewashing (censorship)|whitewashing]] Barnum's life and his perpetuation of [[human zoo]]s as a form of entertainment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-10-21/sydney-opera-house-cabaret-natives-go-wild-first-nations-talent/11442984|title=Coerced, kidnapped, exploited: Dark side of 'Greatest Show on Earth' explored in new show|last=Jefferson|first=arts editor Dee|date=2019-10-21|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width: 99%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n